1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,480
 Now I want to talk a little bit about a concept,

2
00:00:02,480 --> 00:00:05,740
 model view controller, it's not super essential

3
00:00:05,740 --> 00:00:09,260
 to understanding how everything works in web servers,

4
00:00:09,260 --> 00:00:11,060
 but it's a great set of terminology

5
00:00:11,060 --> 00:00:13,820
 that we use among web developers,

6
00:00:13,820 --> 00:00:17,320
 and I think as you move into your role as a web developer,

7
00:00:17,320 --> 00:00:18,780
 you ought to understand this.

8
00:00:18,780 --> 00:00:21,460
 So this is a picture of the request-response cycle.

9
00:00:21,460 --> 00:00:23,320
 At the bottom we have the browser,

10
00:00:23,320 --> 00:00:26,300
 and at the top we have a web server talking on port 80,

11
00:00:26,300 --> 00:00:29,600
 the user clicks on a page, clicks on a link,

12
00:00:29,600 --> 00:00:31,700
 and the browser intercepts that link,

13
00:00:31,700 --> 00:00:33,660
 opens a connection up to the web server,

14
00:00:33,660 --> 00:00:36,680
 sends a get request, the web server does its work,

15
00:00:36,680 --> 00:00:38,120
 and returns a web page.

16
00:00:38,120 --> 00:00:42,300
 And so that's sort of the basic request-response cycle.

17
00:00:42,300 --> 00:00:45,540
 And now we're going to, as in much of this class,

18
00:00:45,540 --> 00:00:47,580
 really expand what we're going to do

19
00:00:47,580 --> 00:00:49,260
 when we're in that web server.

20
00:00:49,260 --> 00:00:52,280
 So that's where we're gonna take a look at this.

21
00:00:52,280 --> 00:00:54,740
 So basically model view controller

22
00:00:54,740 --> 00:00:59,420
 is really a set of terms that allow us to say,

23
00:00:59,420 --> 00:01:02,980
 this aspect, this part of the work

24
00:01:02,980 --> 00:01:04,900
 that's gonna be done in the web server,

25
00:01:04,900 --> 00:01:07,620
 it's either the model, it's the view, or the controller.

26
00:01:07,620 --> 00:01:11,580
 And so the most value that it has is to say,

27
00:01:11,580 --> 00:01:14,320
 oh, that part right there, that's controller.

28
00:01:14,320 --> 00:01:16,860
 So model view controller is independent

29
00:01:16,860 --> 00:01:19,300
 of the programming language that you use,

30
00:01:19,300 --> 00:01:21,660
 independent of the operating system that you use.

31
00:01:21,660 --> 00:01:24,340
 It's pretty universal across the concept,

32
00:01:24,340 --> 00:01:28,500
 as an architecture, as a way of talking about web servers.

33
00:01:29,900 --> 00:01:32,900
 So the three parts of it, it'd be probably better

34
00:01:32,900 --> 00:01:34,780
 to call it controller view model,

35
00:01:34,780 --> 00:01:38,780
 or model controller view model, or something like that.

36
00:01:38,780 --> 00:01:41,520
 But model view controller rolls off our tongue better.

37
00:01:41,520 --> 00:01:44,940
 So the definition in my mind of these terms

38
00:01:44,940 --> 00:01:48,980
 is the controller is this sort of abstract idea

39
00:01:48,980 --> 00:01:52,940
 of what happens next, what is the sequence of events

40
00:01:52,940 --> 00:01:55,260
 that happen, and then where do we start from,

41
00:01:55,260 --> 00:01:57,320
 what do we do when we get a request,

42
00:01:57,320 --> 00:02:00,520
 and then afterwards, where do we go at the end of that?

43
00:02:00,520 --> 00:02:02,600
 The view is all the stuff we see.

44
00:02:02,600 --> 00:02:05,280
 It usually is at the end of the request response cycle,

45
00:02:05,280 --> 00:02:08,300
 we produce a view and we return the view back.

46
00:02:08,300 --> 00:02:11,540
 And one of the things that the request response cycle

47
00:02:11,540 --> 00:02:14,420
 often does is either interacts by storing data

48
00:02:14,420 --> 00:02:18,500
 in a database, like an insert, or it edits something

49
00:02:18,500 --> 00:02:21,020
 and puts it in a database, or it just reads stuff

50
00:02:21,020 --> 00:02:25,500
 from the database and shows it to us in the view.

51
00:02:25,500 --> 00:02:26,900
 And so that's called the model.

52
00:02:26,900 --> 00:02:30,020
 The database itself, and sort of the notion

53
00:02:30,020 --> 00:02:33,300
 that we have persistent storage inside the application,

54
00:02:33,300 --> 00:02:34,660
 that's what we call the model.

55
00:02:34,660 --> 00:02:37,300
 The view is what we see, and the controller's kind of the glue

56
00:02:37,300 --> 00:02:38,860
 that puts it all together.

57
00:02:38,860 --> 00:02:42,060
 So the controller orchestrates all this stuff.

58
00:02:42,060 --> 00:02:45,140
 And so sometimes you don't say that's the controller,

59
00:02:45,140 --> 00:02:47,260
 but the controller is like several places

60
00:02:47,260 --> 00:02:50,260
 and the actual shape of your application.

61
00:02:50,260 --> 00:02:55,600
 So when we receive a request, we have a number of tasks

62
00:02:55,600 --> 00:02:58,600
 that we often have to do for each request.

63
00:02:58,600 --> 00:03:01,580
 Sometimes if it's like a form that's been sent to us,

64
00:03:01,580 --> 00:03:03,780
 we have some data that we have to receive,

65
00:03:03,780 --> 00:03:05,620
 validate, and then process,

66
00:03:05,620 --> 00:03:07,460
 and then store it in a database maybe.

67
00:03:07,460 --> 00:03:10,580
 And so that's often thought of as the model work.

68
00:03:10,580 --> 00:03:13,240
 Then once we've done that, we make a decision,

69
00:03:13,240 --> 00:03:16,440
 like I've stored this, where do we want to send the user?

70
00:03:16,440 --> 00:03:17,700
 What do we want to show next?

71
00:03:17,700 --> 00:03:19,720
 What page to show next?

72
00:03:19,720 --> 00:03:22,140
 Maybe we show them a thank you page,

73
00:03:22,140 --> 00:03:25,860
 or maybe we send them back to the top page of the application.

74
00:03:25,860 --> 00:03:29,140
 And so once we know what page we're gonna send back to them,

75
00:03:29,140 --> 00:03:30,720
 then that page has some data

76
00:03:30,720 --> 00:03:33,200
 that we might have to pull from the database.

77
00:03:33,200 --> 00:03:35,320
 And so we retrieve that using the model,

78
00:03:35,320 --> 00:03:37,980
 and then we produce, perhaps using a template,

79
00:03:37,980 --> 00:03:41,620
 some HTML response, and then put it back.

80
00:03:41,620 --> 00:03:45,180
 So these are the four typical steps that we break down.

81
00:03:45,180 --> 00:03:47,760
 Say, in comes an HTTP request.

82
00:03:47,760 --> 00:03:49,380
 First thing we do is if it has data

83
00:03:49,380 --> 00:03:52,040
 that we're supposed to do something with, we handle it.

84
00:03:52,040 --> 00:03:54,880
 Maybe store that data in a database.

85
00:03:54,880 --> 00:03:57,400
 Then we talk to the database and retrieve more data

86
00:03:57,400 --> 00:03:59,880
 to produce the next output that we're gonna make.

87
00:03:59,880 --> 00:04:03,600
 And then we produce the HTML or the other form of output,

88
00:04:03,600 --> 00:04:06,480
 and we send it back to the browser.

89
00:04:06,480 --> 00:04:10,160
 And so if we take a look at this in our Django application,

90
00:04:10,160 --> 00:04:13,560
 the Django application is pretty much

91
00:04:13,560 --> 00:04:16,360
 a model view controller application

92
00:04:16,360 --> 00:04:21,240
 in that the routing is very much the controller.

93
00:04:21,240 --> 00:04:25,960
 It is that which we, it's like, here comes a URL.

94
00:04:25,960 --> 00:04:27,640
 It's a request for something.

95
00:04:27,640 --> 00:04:28,720
 Where do we go?

96
00:04:28,720 --> 00:04:30,840
 And so when you write urls.py,

97
00:04:30,840 --> 00:04:32,480
 you're informing the controller.

98
00:04:32,480 --> 00:04:34,120
 So the urls.py, I would say,

99
00:04:34,120 --> 00:04:38,000
 is part of the controller action, the controller activity.

100
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:42,060
 The views is named the view.

101
00:04:42,060 --> 00:04:44,900
 So the view is a little bit controller

102
00:04:44,900 --> 00:04:47,600
 in that sometimes the view is storing some data

103
00:04:47,600 --> 00:04:48,440
 in the database.

104
00:04:48,440 --> 00:04:50,800
 Sometimes that's the job of the view.

105
00:04:50,800 --> 00:04:53,600
 Here comes some data before the view produces

106
00:04:53,600 --> 00:04:55,680
 the next output.

107
00:04:55,680 --> 00:04:59,220
 It actually has to store what came in on this request.

108
00:04:59,220 --> 00:05:02,040
 And then the view will do some controller activity,

109
00:05:02,040 --> 00:05:04,560
 like it might decide, you know, I don't want you,

110
00:05:04,560 --> 00:05:07,160
 this is the wrong page now that we've processed your data.

111
00:05:07,160 --> 00:05:09,340
 I'm just gonna send you over to some other page.

112
00:05:09,340 --> 00:05:11,240
 That's kind of a controller activity.

113
00:05:11,240 --> 00:05:13,420
 So it might say, I'll store the data.

114
00:05:13,420 --> 00:05:15,920
 It might, let's see here, can I, yeah.

115
00:05:15,920 --> 00:05:18,120
 So it might say, you know, here I go.

116
00:05:18,120 --> 00:05:19,600
 I'm gonna store some data.

117
00:05:19,600 --> 00:05:21,200
 And then I'm actually just gonna send you

118
00:05:21,200 --> 00:05:22,040
 to a different place.

119
00:05:22,040 --> 00:05:24,160
 So I'm not even gonna give you an HTML.

120
00:05:24,160 --> 00:05:25,720
 And we'll talk about that redirect.

121
00:05:25,720 --> 00:05:28,080
 That's called a redirect in a bit.

122
00:05:28,080 --> 00:05:30,440
 Sometimes there is no data.

123
00:05:30,440 --> 00:05:32,280
 And so sometimes you get some data,

124
00:05:32,280 --> 00:05:33,920
 you route it to the right view,

125
00:05:33,920 --> 00:05:37,320
 and maybe some data has to be retrieved from the database,

126
00:05:37,320 --> 00:05:40,880
 merged together, and result is processed.

127
00:05:40,880 --> 00:05:43,880
 So when we think of views.py,

128
00:05:43,880 --> 00:05:48,880
 that is, to me, both the controller and the view production.

129
00:05:49,080 --> 00:05:52,720
 So sometimes it's making decisions about where to go next.

130
00:05:52,720 --> 00:05:55,000
 Sometimes it's just handling incoming data

131
00:05:55,000 --> 00:05:57,200
 or sending data out.

132
00:05:57,200 --> 00:06:02,200
 And similarly, the models is taken from Model View Controller

133
00:06:02,200 --> 00:06:08,120
 because the models.py is where we basically do all the work

134
00:06:08,120 --> 00:06:10,680
 to talk to the database, whether it is storing stuff

135
00:06:10,680 --> 00:06:12,880
 in the database or retrieving stuff in the database.

136
00:06:12,880 --> 00:06:17,520
 We use the Django model capability to implement the concept

137
00:06:17,520 --> 00:06:20,240
 in Model View Controller of models.

138
00:06:20,240 --> 00:06:22,520
 So just a quick summary.

139
00:06:22,520 --> 00:06:24,960
 I like to think of urls.py

140
00:06:24,960 --> 00:06:28,000
 and some of the views.py is the controller.

141
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:29,640
 The models, of course, is all the things

142
00:06:29,640 --> 00:06:30,960
 that talk to the database.

143
00:06:30,960 --> 00:06:34,640
 And then the views are like the second half of views.py.

144
00:06:34,640 --> 00:06:38,800
 So produce using templates and forms.py and et cetera,

145
00:06:38,800 --> 00:06:41,240
 et cetera to produce the output and send it out.

146
00:06:41,240 --> 00:06:44,560
 And so that's how I map the Model View Controller

147
00:06:44,560 --> 00:06:46,600
 onto the Django architecture.

148
00:06:46,600 --> 00:06:49,600
 And again, Django architecture was probably inspired

149
00:06:49,600 --> 00:06:50,720
 by the Model View Controller.

150
00:06:50,720 --> 00:06:52,960
 And that's why it takes some of its names

151
00:06:52,960 --> 00:06:54,680
 of some of its capabilities

152
00:06:54,680 --> 00:06:56,680
 from the Model View Controller concept.

153
00:06:56,680 --> 00:06:59,260
 (upbeat music)

